For **Azure DevOps Server 2022.2**, use **`api-version=7.0`**, not `7.1`. Microsoft’s REST API versioning page shows Azure DevOps Server 2022 supports REST API versions up to **7.0**. It also says every request must include an API version either in the query string or the `Accept` header. ([Microsoft Learn][1])

So replace your **“Tag source build as last known good”** step with this:

```yaml
- powershell: |
    $ErrorActionPreference = "Stop"

    if ('${{ parameters.tagSuccessfulBuild }}' -ne 'true') {
      Write-Host "Tagging disabled."
      exit 0
    }

    $buildId = "$(DownloadRequestedArtifact.BuildNumber)"
    if ([string]::IsNullOrWhiteSpace($buildId)) {
      throw "Source build id is empty. DownloadRequestedArtifact.BuildNumber was not populated."
    }

    $collectionUri = "$(System.CollectionUri)".TrimEnd('/')
    $projectName   = [System.Uri]::EscapeDataString("$(System.TeamProject)")
    $tag           = '${{ parameters.rollbackTag }}'
    $tagEscaped    = [System.Uri]::EscapeDataString($tag)

    # Azure DevOps Server 2022 supports up to REST API 7.0
    $apiVersion = "7.0"

    $uri = "$collectionUri/$projectName/_apis/build/builds/$buildId/tags/$tagEscaped?api-version=$apiVersion"

    Write-Host "Tagging source build $buildId with '$tag'"
    Write-Host "URI: $uri"

    $headers = @{
      Authorization = "Bearer $env:SYSTEM_ACCESSTOKEN"
      Accept        = "application/json; api-version=$apiVersion"
    }

    Invoke-RestMethod -Method Put -Uri $uri -Headers $headers | Out-Null
    Write-Host "Tagged source build successfully."
  displayName: 'Tag source build as last known good'
  condition: succeeded()
  env:
    SYSTEM_ACCESSTOKEN: $(System.AccessToken)
```

### Why this fixes it

* changes `api-version` from `7.1` to `7.0`, which matches Azure DevOps Server 2022 support ([Microsoft Learn][1])
* sends the version in **both** places:

  * query string
  * `Accept` header
    Microsoft says either method is valid. ([Microsoft Learn][1])
* builds the URL more safely by trimming the collection URL and URL-encoding the project/tag

### One more thing to verify

Make sure the build service identity for this release pipeline has permission to update build metadata/tags. The Build Tags REST API requires build-execute level access. ([Microsoft Learn][2])

